\begin_layout Title
\noindent
Response to Reviewers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
The authors express thanks to the editors and reviewers for taking the time
 to review the manuscript, and for insightful comments and recommendations
 to strengthen the quality and readability of the manuscript.
 We have modified the manuscript to respond to concerns raised by the reviewers
 and have elaborated on the changes below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*

\size larger
Comments from, and Responses to the Editor
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
I have received two reviews of this paper from experts in this field.
 Both agree that the paper is worthy of investigation and offers a relevant
 contribution to the literature.
 However, both reviewers raise a variety of concerns about the empirical
 methodology and give several other important detailed comments that should
 be addressed in a major revision before the paper is publishable.
 I am looking forward to receiving the revised version of this paper, and
 encourage the authors to respond to all comments of both reviewers.
 An additional suggestion I have is to better frame the paper in a water
 context, so that it has a stronger link with the theme of the journal Water
 Resources and Economics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thank you for the opportunity to revise and resubmit the manuscript.
 We have included a paragraph in the introduction that better frames the
 paper in a water context, and through out the paper (where possible), we
 have made efforts to frame the paper to better suit the journal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*

\size larger
Comments from, and Responses to Reviewer 1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Comment 1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
First of all, the analysis of the ENSO effects is starting from the measure
 of ENSO i.e., SSTA.
 There is no obvious explanation in the manuscript as to why the choice
 of Brunner(2002) to also include the Southern Oscillation Index (SOI) anomalies
 was not considered.
 Clearly in this case, the results become over-complicated but I think this
 should be at least mentioned as a sensitivity analysis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
\noindent

\series bold
Response to Comment 1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Agreed.
 We have now made it clearer in the paper on why we focus on the SSTA and
 not on the SOI as the measure of ENSO.
 In the paper, we state that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

While some papers have used the Southern Oscillation Index (SOI) anomalies
 to capture ENSO events, this paper exclusively uses SSTA for several reasons.
 First, the official measure of ENSO used by the NOAA - the Oceanic Niño
 Index (ONI) - is based on sea surface temperatures in the east-central
 tropical Pacific Ocean.
 It is perhaps for this reason that SSTA are the most widely used ENSO indicator
 in academic research (see e.g.
 Hansen et al., 1998; Brunner, 2002; and Berry and Okulicz-Kozaryn, 2008).
 Second, the SOI is calculated as the difference between the atmospheric
 pressure at sea level over Tahiti and over Darwin, Australia.
 As pointed out by the NOAA, the fact that the SOI is derived from sea level
 pressure over just two stations implies that shorter term sea level pressure
 fluctuations not related to ENSO can affect the SOI.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
https://www.climate.gov/news-features/blogs/enso/why-are-there-so-many-enso-indexe
s-instead-just-one
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Third, the two stations over which sea level pressure data are collected
 to estimate the SOI - Tahiti and Darwin - are located south of the equator
 (Tahiti at 18˚S, Darwin at 12˚S).
 ENSO, however, is typically focused closer to the equator.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As the reviewer notes, results become over-complicated when SOI is used.
 Even though it is an alternative measure of ENSO, it has several drawbacks.
 In addition, note that even though Brunner (2002) also uses SOI, the responses
 of many of the variables in his model to a shock to SOI are not significantly
 different from zero, while the responses to SSTA shocks are different from
 zero.
 Other authors have found similar results when using the SOI.
\end_layout

