\begin_layout Subsubsection*
\noindent

\series bold
Response to Comment 6
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Agreed.
 However, we used the S&P 500 to make exactly the point the reviewer just
 made.
 That is, we used the S&P 500 index to show that a broad measure such as
 the S&P 500 might be too indifferent to shocks to ENSO, making it necessary
 to study individual food and agricultural stock returns.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition, while we would have liked to use the S&P Agribusiness North
 America Index, this index is only available from June 2008.
 After differencing and taking lags into account, estimating an 8-variable
 VAR model with such short time series results in serious degrees of freedom
 issues, making inference impossible.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Comment 7
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Your analysis is based on a simple VAR.
 Clearly this methodology is unable to capture the non-linearities in the
 system dynamics as was shown by Ubilava, David, 2017.
 "The ENSO Effect and Asymmetries in Wheat Price Dynamics," World Development,
 Elsevier, vol.
 96(C), pages 490-502.
 The authors do not have to go into the trouble of applying this methodology
 but they should at least mention it in the manuscript.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
\noindent

\series bold
Response to Comment 7
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Agreed.
 A simple VAR model does not capture nonlinearities, to the extent that
 such nonlinearities are present.
 However, using the nonlinear approaches used by, for example, Ubilava (2017)
 are also problematic.
 First, the nonlinear time series literature suggests a host of nonlinear
 methods.
 In the end, whichever method one chooses is somewhat arbitrary.
 For example one could choose to model these nonlinearities using Threshold
 VAR models, Smooth Transition models, Regime Switching models, etc.
 There is no theory as to which nonlinear alternative is most appropriate,
 especially for a study like ours.
 Second, with these nonlinear methods, the usual impulse response functions
 and forecast error variance decomposition will no longer be applicable.
 As a result, we have rewritten the manuscript to focus on the main results
 from the linear VAR model, leaving the question of possible nonlinearities
 for future research.
 This has been mentioned in the conclusion of the paper.
\end_layout

