Comment 8
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
As far as the lags used in the VAR, I am a bit surprised about the result
 of k=1 but of course that can be a result of the two criteria used here.
 Nevertheless, these tests are just to give some guidance.
 As a rule of thumb, I would always start with 12 lags in the case of monthly
 data in long series in order to cover seasonality.
 Does that change the results significantly?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
\noindent

\series bold
Response to Comment 8
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Agreed.
 In the baseline results, we selected the lag length using the SIC which
 selected 3 lags.
 In a robustness section, we estimated the VAR models using 12 lags of the
 endogenous variables.
 As shown in Figure 6 of the revised manuscript, the results are quite robust
 to alternative lag lengths.
\end_layout

