\begin_layout Subsection*

\size larger
Comments from, and Responses to Reviewer 2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Comment 1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
The paper does not include a discussion on the determinants of U.S.
 stock returns.
 As is well known, in the literature there are three recognized determinants
 of stock market returns, namely inflation, inflation uncertainty, and foreign
 exchange rate.
 Even though the paper considers inflation, theory indicates that higher
 inflation is caused by higher inflation uncertainty, with the direction
 of causality going from inflation uncertainty to inflation.
 Thus, the assumed relation is between inflation uncertainty, and not inflation,
 and stock returns as the author states.
 This is due to the fact that higher inflation uncertainty increases the
 required risk premium, lead to a higher discount rate, and lowers the discounte
d present value of expected future cash flows, thus resulting in a fall
 in stock prices.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Regarding the relation between U.S.
 stock returns and the U.S.
 dollar, there is a theoretical justification for a link between stock returns
 and the foreign exchange rate.
 A depreciation of the foreign exchange rate makes export-oriented firms
 more competitive and they generate more profits from international trade.
 Therefore, since stock returns are equal to discounted future cash flows,
 and since higher earnings mean higher cash flows, then stock returns are
 positively impacted.
 Nonetheless, such a relationship breaks down, and changes sign, if firms
 are imported oriented, relying on foreign inputs into their production
 process.
 In such a case, a depreciation of the foreign exchange rate raises the
 cost of inputs and reduce profits, lowering stock prices.
 In both cases, the causality runs from the foreign exchange rate to the
 stock prices.
 Therefore, the author must include on the model the foreign exchange rate
 to check the robustness of his results.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Response to Comment 1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Section 3.1 of the revised manuscript now includes a discussion of the determinan
ts of stock returns.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Comment 2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Unit root tests indicated that ENSO measures are I(0) whereas the macroeconomic
 and stock prices are I(1) in log levels and I(0) in log first differences.
 Without showing that there is no evidence of cointegration among the variables
 in log levels, the author decides to estimate equation (2) as a VAR in
 first differences.
 However, this approach would be suboptimal if it was determined these series
 are indeed cointegrated.
 In that case, the VAR would only express the short-run responses of these
 series to innovations in each series.
 If the series are cointegrated, they move together in the long-run.
 A VAR in first differences, although properly specified in terms of covariance-
stationary series, will not capture those long-run tendencies.
 The author must show evidence of no cointegration among the variables in
 log levels; otherwise, model (2) must include an error correction term.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Response to Comment 2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The finding that some variables are stationary in levels, while others are
 stationary only after first differences rules out the need to test for
 cointegration.
 Testing for cointegration is only necessary if all the variables potentially
 entering the VAR model contain a unit root.
 As Table 3 shows, this is not the case for all our variables, hence, a
 VAR model in differences is appropriate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Comment 3
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Strictly speaking, model 2 is a recursive VAR, where the variables are assumed
 to form a recursive dynamic structural model where each variable only depends
 upon those above it in the vector.
 On the other hand, a structural VAR is where theory is used to place restrictio
ns on the contemporaneous correlations.
 The author must be careful using the structural VAR concept.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
In the dynamic structural equation model (equation 2), the ordering of the
 recursive structure is that imposed in the Cholesky decomposition, which
 is that in which the endogenous variables appear in the model estimation.
 As this choice is somewhat arbitrary, the author must explore the impulse
 response functions from a different ordering to check for results robustness.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Response to Comment 3
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Agreed.
 We have made this clear in the paper.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have provided evidence in the paper that results remain unchanged when
 we estimate the VAR models with the reverse ordering of the variables.
 Of course, this ordering is simply to ensure robustness of the results,
 but is not very meaningful, as it is, for example, unlikely that agricultural
 stock returns affect ENSO contemporaneously.
 The main results of the paper follow the convention of ordering the more
 exogenous variables ahead of the less exogenous ones.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Comment 4
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
The author conjecture that responses to ENSO shocks are asymmetric- a strong
 el Niño event may result in stock returns dynamics very different than
 those associated with a strong la Niña event.
 This latter observation suggests that standard linear models including
 Vector Autoregression (VAR) or Vector Error Corrections Models (VECMs)
 may not be appropriated for examining asymmetric relationships between
 ENSO events and agriculture stock returns.
 Therefore, equation (2) must be extended to a nonlinear alternative model
 such as the Smooth Transition Autoregression (STAR) model or the Markov-Switchi
ng Vector Autoregression model.
 (See, for instance, Ubilava D.
 and Holt M.
 (2013).
 El niño southern oscillation and its effects on world vegetable oil prices:
 assessing asymmetries using smooth transition models.
 The Australian Journal of Agricultural and Resource Economics; for the
 use of nonlinear models).
 Otherwise, the author must explain how the use of the VAR model on subsamples
 address regime-dependent asymmetries on the nonlinear relationship between
 ENSO shocks and stock returns.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Response to Comment 4
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have refocused the paper on the main effects of ENSO, leaving out the
 question of possible asymmetries/nonlinearities for future research.
 The reviewer is absolutely right that if ENSO has asymmetric or nonlinear
 effects, then a simple linear VAR model estimated over different subsamples
 does not address the issue of regime dependence across subsamples.
 However, the nonlinear time series approaches are also problematic.
 First, the nonlinear time series literature suggests a host of nonlinear
 methods, including Threshold VAR models, Smooth Transition (Vector) Autoregress
ive models, Markov Switching State Space models, and the subcategories of
 these models.
 The issue then becomes suppose we test for linearity against a variety
 of possible nonlinear alternatives.
 In most cases, a rejection of linearity does not tell the researcher which
 nonlinear specification is most appropriate.
 In that case, choosing a given nonlinear alternative is just as arbitrary
 as the VAR model.
 In addition, with these nonlinear methods, the usual impulse response functions
 and forecast error variance decomposition will no longer be applicable.
 As a result, we have rewritten the manuscript to focus on the main results
 from the linear VAR model, leaving the question of possible nonlinearities
 for future research.
 This has been mentioned in the conclusion of the paper.
\end_layout

